    'refactor',
    'Split users table into admin_users + app_users (per-kind email uniqueness)',
    E'## What it does\n\nSplits the unified `users` table into two disjoint tables â€” `admin_users` (rows with system_role) and `app_users` (rows without). A read-only VIEW called `users` UNIONs them so existing SELECT-from-users queries continue to work without per-call refactoring.\n\nEmail uniqueness is now scoped per kind: the same email may exist as an admin AND as a parent (two rows, two passwords, two sessions). This is required for community-leader scenarios where one person needs both an admin portal account (limited system_role) and a parent app account.\n\n## Why\n\n- Bryan needs to test partner-role login on prod, but joe@workmaninsurancegroup.com already existed as a prod parent â€” the global unique-email constraint blocked creating an admin row for the same email.\n- More broadly: as the platform onboards "community leaders who are also parents and have limited admin roles", the global unique constraint becomes a hard block. Splitting into per-kind tables fixes this by construction and improves PHI containment (the future admin-user replication slice can mirror admin_users only â€” parent rows never touch the cross-env wire).\n\n## Schema changes (migration 00032)\n\n- Created `admin_users` and `app_users` with their own `UNIQUE(email)` constraints.\n- Copied rows from `users` partitioned by `system_role IS NULL`, preserving every UUID. Any FK reference is still a valid UUID after the move.\n- Retargeted ~50 FK constraints to either `admin_users.id` or `app_users.id` based on column semantics: `*.logged_by`, `*.user_id` on logging tables, `*.created_by` on app-side tables â†’ app_users; `admin_*.admin_id`, `*.deactivated_by`, `*.comped_by`, `*.awarded_by`, `version_log.created_by`, etc. â†’ admin_users.\n- `audit_log.user_id` split into `admin_id` + `app_user_id` (mixed-actor column).\n- `sessions.user_id` split similarly; `sessions` was TRUNCATEd during migration (8h-max sessions, force-relogin acceptable).\n- Defensive cleanup before FK retargets: NULLed orphaned admin-context refs to demoted users (admin_audit_log had 1 such row on dev, prod-clone dry-run found similar small numbers â€” graceful degradation).\n- Created a backward-compat read-only VIEW `users` that UNIONs the two tables.\n\n## Code changes\n\n- `userRepo.GetAdminByEmail` / `GetAppByEmail`: kind-aware lookups for login flows.\n- `AuthService.LoginWithContext`: routes to the right lookup based on `LoginContext.Kind`.\n- `AuthService.Register`: uses `GetAppByEmail` for duplicate check (admin row with same email is allowed by design).\n- `AdminRepository.CreateAdminUser`: writes admin_users; `RemoveAdminRole` now DELETES the admin row (was: NULL system_role, no longer valid since admin_users.system_role is NOT NULL).\n- `userRepo.UpdateStatus / UpdateLastLogin / Delete`: fan out to both tables (only one matches).\n- `password_reset_service`: updates both tables.\n- `cmd/createadmin`: writes admin_users.\n- `session_repo.Create`: writes admin_id or app_user_id based on Kind. Reads COALESCE both back into Session.UserID.\n\n## Safety\n\n- Pre-migration full pg_dump of dev + prod stored in /home/carecomp/secrets/db_backups/ AND s3://carecompanion-db-backups/ (versioned + AES256 encrypted).\n- Per-table CSV extract of Joe Steinmetz family data captured separately.\n- Migration is one transaction with inline integrity assertions (RAISE EXCEPTION on count mismatch).\n- Matching revert script at `scripts/revert-split-users.sql`.\n- Dry-run on prod-clone (Docker postgres on admin EC2 restored from prod dump): forward â†’ revert â†’ forward round-trip verified Matty Steinmetz''s 409 medication_logs preserved bit-equivalent through every transition.\n- Post-deploy: re-extracted Joe''s prod data and diffed field-by-field against the pre-migration extract â€” zero differences confirmed.\n\n## Coexists with\n\nThis is the schema foundation for the bidirectional admin-user replication slice (which depends on `admin_users` existing on both envs). Replication ships as a separate slice.\n\n## Commits\n\n47d74a8 feat(schema): split users table into admin_users + app_users (00032)',
    :version,
    :author
);
